    {"intent_id": "comp_largest_ocean", "query": "what is the largest ocean", "response": "The Pacific Ocean is the largest at 165.25 million km², covering more area than all land on Earth combined. It spans from the Americas to Asia and Australia. Deepest point: Challenger Deep in the Mariana Trench at ~11,034m (36,201 ft). Named by Ferdinand Magellan in 1520 ('peaceful sea').", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "comp_deepest_ocean", "query": "what is the deepest point in the ocean", "response": "The Challenger Deep in the Mariana Trench is the deepest known point at ~11,034 meters (36,201 feet) below sea level. Located in the western Pacific near Guam. First reached by Jacques Piccard and Don Walsh in 1960 (Trieste), later by James Cameron (2012) and Victor Vescovo (2019).", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "comp_oldest_civilization", "query": "what is the oldest civilization", "response": "Mesopotamia (modern Iraq) is generally considered the cradle of civilization, with Sumer emerging around 4500-4000 BC. Ancient Egypt followed (~3100 BC), then the Indus Valley (~3300 BC), and China's Shang Dynasty (~1600 BC). Göbekli Tepe in Turkey (~9500 BC) predates all but isn't considered a full civilization.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "comp_hottest_planet", "query": "what is the hottest planet", "response": "Venus is the hottest planet at ~465°C (869°F) surface temperature — hotter than Mercury despite being farther from the Sun. Its thick CO₂ atmosphere creates an extreme greenhouse effect. Atmospheric pressure is 92 times Earth's. Sulfuric acid clouds reflect sunlight, making it the brightest planet in our sky.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "comp_coldest_place", "query": "what is the coldest place on earth", "response": "The coldest recorded temperature is -89.2°C (-128.6°F) at Vostok Station, Antarctica on July 21, 1983. Satellite data suggests some Antarctic plateaus may reach -98°C. Coldest inhabited place: Oymyakon, Russia, with a recorded -67.7°C (-89.9°F). Average winter temperatures there: -50°C.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "comp_longest_river", "query": "what is the longest river", "response": "The Nile River at ~6,650 km (4,130 miles), flowing through 11 African countries from Burundi to Egypt. The Amazon is close (~6,400 km) and carries far more water — about 20% of all river water entering oceans. Debate continues over exact measurements due to source identification.", "variant": "short"},
