    # ── WHO INVENTED / CREATED ────────────────────────────────────────────
    {"intent_id": "who_python", "query": "who invented Python", "response": "Python was created by Guido van Rossum and first released in 1991. He started working on it in the late 1980s at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands. Named after Monty Python, not the snake. Guido was 'Benevolent Dictator For Life' (BDFL) until stepping down in 2018.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "who_javascript", "query": "who created JavaScript", "response": "JavaScript was created by Brendan Eich at Netscape in just 10 days in May 1995. Originally called Mocha, then LiveScript, then JavaScript (for marketing — unrelated to Java). Standardized as ECMAScript. Now the most widely used programming language, running in every browser and on servers via Node.js.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "who_linux", "query": "who created Linux", "response": "Linux was created by Linus Torvalds in 1991 as a free alternative to MINIX. He announced it on a Usenet newsgroup as 'just a hobby, won't be big and professional.' Now powers most servers, Android phones, supercomputers, and cloud infrastructure. The kernel is open-source; GNU tools complete the OS.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "who_internet", "query": "who invented the internet", "response": "The internet evolved from ARPANET (1969), funded by the US Department of Defense. Key contributors: Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn (TCP/IP, 1974), Tim Berners-Lee (World Wide Web, 1989 at CERN), Marc Andreessen (Mosaic browser, 1993). No single inventor — it was a collaborative effort over decades.", "variant": "detailed"},
    {"intent_id": "who_bitcoin", "query": "who created Bitcoin", "response": "Bitcoin was created by the pseudonymous Satoshi Nakamoto, who published the whitepaper 'Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System' in October 2008. The first block (genesis block) was mined January 3, 2009. Satoshi's identity remains unknown — they disappeared from public communication in 2011.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "who_google", "query": "who founded Google", "response": "Google was founded by Larry Page and Sergey Brin in September 1998 while they were PhD students at Stanford University. Started in a garage in Menlo Park, California. Originally called 'Backrub.' The name 'Google' is a play on 'googol' (10^100). Now part of Alphabet Inc. (since 2015).", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "who_apple", "query": "who founded Apple", "response": "Apple was founded by Steve Jobs, Steve Wozniak, and Ronald Wayne on April 1, 1976. Wozniak built the Apple I computer; Jobs handled business and vision. Wayne sold his 10% stake for $800 (worth ~$400 billion today). Apple became the first company to reach $3 trillion market cap in 2023.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "who_electricity", "query": "who discovered electricity", "response": "Electricity wasn't discovered by one person. Key milestones: Benjamin Franklin (lightning is electrical, 1752), Alessandro Volta (first battery, 1800), Michael Faraday (electromagnetic induction, 1831), Thomas Edison (practical light bulb, 1879), Nikola Tesla (AC power system, 1880s). Ancient Greeks knew about static electricity from amber.", "variant": "detailed"},
    {"intent_id": "who_telephone", "query": "who invented the telephone", "response": "Alexander Graham Bell patented the telephone in 1876, though Antonio Meucci and Elisha Gray also developed similar devices around the same time. Bell's patent (No. 174,465) is one of the most valuable ever. The first words transmitted: 'Mr. Watson, come here, I want to see you.' The US Congress recognized Meucci's contributions in 2002.", "variant": "short"},

    # ── WHEN / HISTORY OF ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
    {"intent_id": "when_internet", "query": "when was the internet created", "response": "ARPANET, the internet's predecessor, sent its first message on October 29, 1969 between UCLA and Stanford. TCP/IP was adopted in 1983 (often considered the internet's 'birthday'). Tim Berners-Lee invented the World Wide Web in 1989. The first website went live in 1991. Commercial use exploded in the mid-1990s.", "variant": "detailed"},
    {"intent_id": "when_python", "query": "when was Python created", "response": "Python was first released on February 20, 1991 (version 0.9.0). Python 2.0 came in 2000 (list comprehensions, garbage collection). Python 3.0 in 2008 (backward-incompatible cleanup). Python 2 reached end-of-life January 1, 2020. Current: Python 3.12+ with significant performance improvements.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "when_moon_landing", "query": "when did humans first land on the moon", "response": "Apollo 11 landed on the Moon on July 20, 1969. Neil Armstrong was the first person to walk on the lunar surface, followed by Buzz Aldrin. Michael Collins orbited above in the command module. Armstrong's words: 'That's one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind.' Six Apollo missions landed in total (1969-1972).", "variant": "detailed"},
    {"intent_id": "when_dinosaurs", "query": "when did dinosaurs go extinct", "response": "Non-avian dinosaurs went extinct ~66 million years ago at the end of the Cretaceous period. Caused by the Chicxulub asteroid impact (10-15 km wide) in modern-day Mexico, combined with massive volcanic activity (Deccan Traps in India). Birds are the surviving descendants of theropod dinosaurs.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "when_ww1", "query": "when was World War 1", "response": "World War I lasted from July 28, 1914 to November 11, 1918. Triggered by the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary. Involved the Allied Powers (France, UK, Russia, later US) vs Central Powers (Germany, Austria-Hungary, Ottoman Empire). ~20 million deaths. Ended with the Treaty of Versailles.", "variant": "short"},

    # ── WHY / REASONS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    {"intent_id": "why_python_slow", "query": "why is Python slow", "response": "Python is slow compared to C/Rust because: 1) Interpreted, not compiled to machine code. 2) Dynamic typing requires runtime type checks. 3) GIL limits true multi-threading. 4) Object overhead — everything is an object, even integers. Mitigations: NumPy/C extensions, PyPy (JIT), Cython, asyncio for I/O, multiprocessing for CPU.", "variant": "list"},
    {"intent_id": "why_python_popular", "query": "why is Python so popular", "response": "Python is popular because: readable syntax (close to English), gentle learning curve, massive ecosystem (pip has 500K+ packages), versatile (web, data science, AI, scripting, automation), strong community, used in education, backed by major companies (Google, Meta, Netflix). Trade-off: slower execution than compiled languages.", "variant": "list"},
    {"intent_id": "why_sky_blue", "query": "why is the sky blue", "response": "The sky is blue due to Rayleigh scattering. Sunlight contains all colors. When it hits Earth's atmosphere, shorter wavelengths (blue/violet) scatter more than longer ones (red/orange). Our eyes are more sensitive to blue than violet, so we see blue. At sunset, light travels through more atmosphere, scattering away blue and leaving red/orange.", "variant": "detailed"},
    {"intent_id": "why_ocean_salty", "query": "why is the ocean salty", "response": "Ocean salt comes from two sources: rivers dissolving minerals from rocks and carrying them to the sea over billions of years, and hydrothermal vents on the ocean floor releasing dissolved minerals. The ocean is ~3.5% salt (mostly sodium chloride). It doesn't get saltier because salt is also removed by organisms and chemical reactions.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "why_leaves_change_color", "query": "why do leaves change color in fall", "response": "In fall, shorter days trigger trees to stop producing chlorophyll (green pigment). As chlorophyll breaks down, hidden pigments are revealed: carotenoids (yellow, orange) were always there. Anthocyanins (red, purple) are newly produced from trapped sugars. Brown comes from tannins. Deciduous trees drop leaves to conserve water in winter.", "variant": "detailed"},
    {"intent_id": "why_yawn", "query": "why do we yawn", "response": "The exact reason is debated. Leading theories: brain cooling (yawning draws cool air to regulate brain temperature), increasing alertness (stretching jaw muscles, increasing heart rate), and social contagion (yawning is 'contagious' — seeing or thinking about yawning triggers it). It's NOT primarily about oxygen levels, as once believed.", "variant": "short"},

