    {"intent_id": "vs_sql_nosql", "query": "should I use SQL or NoSQL", "response": "SQL (PostgreSQL, MySQL) if: structured data, complex queries, joins, ACID transactions, data integrity matters. NoSQL (MongoDB, DynamoDB) if: flexible schema, horizontal scaling, simple access patterns, document/key-value data, rapid iteration. Default to SQL unless you have a specific reason for NoSQL. PostgreSQL handles most use cases well.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "vs_aws_gcp_azure", "query": "should I use AWS GCP or Azure", "response": "AWS: largest market share (~32%), most services, best for startups and general use. GCP: best for AI/ML (Vertex AI), data analytics (BigQuery), Kubernetes (GKE). Azure: best for Microsoft shops (.NET, Active Directory), enterprise, hybrid cloud. For learning: AWS has most job demand. For AI: GCP. For enterprise: Azure. All three are capable.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "vs_mac_windows_linux", "query": "should I use Mac Windows or Linux for programming", "response": "Mac: Unix-based (great for web dev), best for iOS development, premium hardware, 'just works.' Linux: free, most server-like environment, full control, best for DevOps/systems. Windows: best for .NET/C#, gaming, WSL2 gives Linux compatibility. Most web developers use Mac or Linux. Use what your team uses. All three work fine.", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "vs_monolith_microservices", "query": "should I use monolith or microservices", "response": "Start with a monolith unless you have a strong reason not to. Monolith: simpler to develop, test, deploy, and debug. Microservices: when you need independent scaling, multiple teams working in parallel, or different tech stacks per service. Premature microservices is a common mistake. Extract services from a monolith when boundaries become clear.", "variant": "short"},

    # ── ELECTRONICS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    {"intent_id": "elec_transistor", "query": "what is a transistor", "response": "A transistor is a semiconductor device that switches or amplifies electrical signals. Made of doped silicon (NPN or PNP). A small current/voltage at the base/gate controls a larger current flow. Foundation of all modern electronics — billions in a CPU. Types: BJT (current-controlled), MOSFET (voltage-controlled).", "variant": "short"},
    {"intent_id": "elec_cpu", "query": "how does a CPU work", "response": "A CPU executes instructions in a fetch-decode-execute cycle. Fetch: read instruction from memory. Decode: determine the operation. Execute: perform it (arithmetic, logic, memory access). Modern CPUs: pipelining (overlap stages), multiple cores, branch prediction, cache hierarchy (L1/L2/L3). Clock speed measured in GHz.", "variant": "detailed"},
    {"intent_id": "elec_ram_vs_storage", "query": "what is the difference between RAM and storage", "response": "RAM (Random Access Memory): volatile, fast (nanoseconds), temporary — holds active data and programs. Cleared when powered off. Storage (SSD/HDD): non-volatile, slower (microseconds-milliseconds), permanent — holds files, OS, apps. RAM: 8-64GB typical. Storage: 256GB-4TB typical. Both measured in bytes.", "variant": "short"},

